# Step 4 — Optional: handle broken **image** URLs gracefully (no server change needed)

Given many missing historical media under `/wp-content/uploads/...` (2015–2016), you can **avoid broken image icons** site-wide using a tiny client-side fallback (no .htaccess changes):

```html
<!-- Add this new file and include it after your main JS on pages that show legacy media -->
<script defer src="/assets/js/img-fallback.js"></script>
```

```javascript
// /assets/js/img-fallback.js
(function () {
  const PLACEHOLDER = "/assets/img/placeholder.webp"; // create this asset
  document.addEventListener(
    "error",
    (ev) => {
      const el = ev.target;
      if (el && el.tagName === "IMG" && !el.dataset.fallbackApplied) {
        el.dataset.fallbackApplied = "1";
        el.alt = el.alt || "Image unavailable";
        el.src = PLACEHOLDER;
      }
    },
    true // capture to catch <img> load errors
  );
})();
```

**Why this?** Your audits show numerous 404s in `/wp-content/uploads/...`; this keeps pages tidy while you decide whether to restore those files or leave them gone. fileciteturn11file1

> Alternative (server-side, optional): if you **prefer** a server fix for images, you can add a *second* small .htaccess block to serve a placeholder image when an upload file is missing (still no redirects). Only do this if you’re comfortable editing .htaccess again:
> ```apache
> # OPTIONAL: serve a placeholder when an upload image is missing
> <IfModule mod_rewrite.c>
>   RewriteCond %{REQUEST_URI} ^/wp-content/uploads/ [NC]
>   RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f
>   RewriteRule \.(png|jpe?g|gif|webp|svg)$ /assets/img/placeholder.webp [L]
> </IfModule>
> ```
> This affects images only (it won’t mask page 404s).

